1\n |encyclopedia=[[Grove Music Online]]\n |title=Bull [Boul, Bul, Bol], John\n |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]\n |language=English\n |location=London, England\n |doi=10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.article.04294\n |url-access=subscription\n |url=https://www.oxfordmusiconline.com/grovemusic/view/10.1093/gmo/9781561592630.001.0001/omo-9781561592630-e-0000004294\n |ref={{sfnRef|Neighbour|2001}}\n}}\n\n*{{cite journal\n |last=Thewlis\n |first=George A.\n |date=Jan 1940\n |title=Oxford and the Gibbons Family\n |journal=Music & Letters\n |volume=21\n |issue=1\n |pages=31\u201333\n |jstor=727619\n |doi=10.1093/ml/XXI.1.31\n |ref={{sfnRef|Thewlis|1940}}\n }}\n\n*{{cite encyclopedia\n |last=Turbet\n |first=Richard\n |year=2016\n |encyclopedia=[[Oxford Bibliographies Online|Oxford Bibliographies]]\n |title=Orlando Gibbons\n |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]\n |language=English\n |location=London, England\n |doi-access=free\n |doi=10.1093/OBO/9780199757824-0172\n |url=https://www.oxfordbibliographies.com/view/document/obo-9780199757824/obo-9780199757824-0172.xml\n |ref={{sfnRef|Turbet|2016}}\n }}\n\n'''Online'''\n*{{cite web\n |last=Cummings\n |first=Robert\n |website=[[AllMusic]]\n |title=Orlando Gibbons\n |publisher=AllMusic, Netaktion LLC\n |language=English\n |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/orlando-gibbons-mn0001473123/biography\n |ref={{sfnRef|Cummings}}\n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n |last=Rockwell\n |first=John\n |authorlink=John Rockwell\n |date=11 May 1984\n |title=MUSIC: ORLANDO GIBBONS\n |work=[[New York Times]]\n |publisher=The New York Times Company\n |location=New York City, New York\n |accessdate=23 April 2020\n |url-access=limited\n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/05/11/arts/music-orlando-gibbons.html\n |ref={{sfnRef|Rockwell|1984}}\n }}\n\n*{{cite web\n |website=[[Westminster Abbey]]\n |title=Orlando and Christopher Gibbons\n |publisher=Dean and Chapter of Westminster\n |language=English\n |location=London, England\n |url=http://www.westminster-abbey.org/our-history/people/orlando-and-christopher-gibbons\n |ref={{sfnRef|Westminster Abbey}}\n }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Orlando Gibbons}}\n* {{Britannica|233191}}\n*[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/39935/39935-h/39935-h.htm Chapter on Orlando Gibbons in The Project Gutenberg E-text of Twelve Good Musicians, by Frederick Bridge]\n*{{librivox author|Orlando+Gibbons}}\n*[http://www.grovemusic.com Grove Music Online] John Harper: 'Gibbons, Orlando', ed. L. Macy (Accessed 4 January 2007)\n*{{ChoralWiki}}\n*{{IMSLP|id=Gibbons, Orlando|cname=Orlando Gibbons}}\n*[http://www.mutopiaproject.org/cgibin/make-table.cgi?Composer=GibbonsO Free scores] at the [[Mutopia Project]]\n*[http://www.orlandogibbons.com Orlando Gibbons Dedicated Website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Parsons (organist)|John Parsons]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Director of Music|Organist and Master of the Choristers]] of [[Westminster Abbey]]\n|years=1623\u20131625}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Thomas Day (organist)|Thomas Day]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Orlando Gibbons}}\n{{English Virginalist School}}\n{{Renaissance music}}\n{{Baroque music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibbons, Orlando}}\n[[Category:16th-century births]]\n[[Category:1583 births]]\n[[Category:1625 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English Baroque composers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Canterbury Cathedral]]\n[[Category:Composers for harpsichord]]\n[[Category:Composers of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:English madrigal composers]]\n[[Category:English classical composers]]\n[[Category:English male classical composers]]\n[[Category:Renaissance composers]]\n[[Category:English classical organists]]\n[[Category:Male organists]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen of the Chapel Royal]]\n[[Category:Master of the Choristers at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:People from Oxford]]\n[[Category:17th-century English composers]]\n[[Category:17th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:17th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:Choristers of the Choir of King's College, Cambridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English Renaissance composer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n<!-- Before adding an infobox, please consult [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Composers#Biographical infoboxes]] and seek consensus on this article's talk page. -->\n[[File:Orlando Gibbons.jpg|thumb|250px|alt=Portrait of Orlando Gibbons|Portrait or Orlando Gibbons by an unknown artist.{{#tag:ref|This portrait is kept at Faculty of music and [[Bate Collection of Musical Instruments|The Bate Collection of Musical Instruments]] at the [[University of Oxford]] and is only known to be a \"copy from a lost original once in the possession of a Mrs. Fussell.\"|group=n}}]]\n\n'''Orlando Gibbons''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=Pronunciation of Orlando Gibbons.wav|\u0254\u02d0|\u02c8|l|\u00e6|n|d|\u0259|\u028a|_|\u02c8|g|\u026a|b|\u0259|n|z}};<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ttsmp3.com/|title=Orlando Gibbons|work=[[Amazon Polly|AWS Polly]]|accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref> [[baptism|baptised]] 25 December 1583{{spaced ndash}}5 June 1625) was an English [[composer]], [[virginalist]] and [[organist]] of the [[Elizabethan era|Elizabethan]] (late [[Tudor period|Tudor]]) and early [[Jacobean era|Jacobean periods]]. Due to his sudden and early death, Gibbons' output was not as large as that of his older contemporary [[William Byrd]], but he still managed to produce various [[secular]] and [[sacred]] [[polyphony|polyphonic]] vocal works, including [[Consort song (musical)|consort songs]], [[service (music)|services]], [[motets]], more than 40 [[anthem|full anthems]] and [[verse anthem|verse anthems]], a set of 20 [[madrigals]] as well as at least 20 keyboard works and various [[instrumental]] ensemble pieces including nearly 30 [[Fantasia (music)|fantasies]] for [[Viol|viols]]. He is well known for the 5-part verse anthem ''[[This Is the Record of John]]'', the 8-part full anthem ''O Clap Your Hands Together'', 2 settings of [[Evening Prayer (Anglican)|Evensong]] and what is often thought to be the best known English madrigal: ''[[The Silver Swan (song)|The Silver Swan]]''.\n\nBorn in [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], Gibbons was born into a musical family where his father, William Gibbons, was a [[wait (musician)|wait]],{{#tag:ref|This would indicate that William was either an instrumentalist, singer or perhaps both.|group=n}} his children being expected to follow his footsteps in the trade. It is not known with whom he studied composition, although it may have been with an older brother or his father. Gibbons was certainly acquainted with William Byrd and [[John Bull (composer)|John Bull]], and the three later collectively published the first printed book of keyboard music, ''[[Parthenia (music)|Parthenia]]''. Since Bull was a student of Byrd it is possible that Gibbons was as well; however, there is no supporting evidence of this.\n\nIrrespective of his education, he was musically proficient enough to be appointed by [[James VI and I|King James I]] a [[Gentleman of the Chapel Royal|gentleman]] of the [[Chapel Royal]] around May of 1603 and a senior organist by 1605. By 1606 he had graduated from [[King's College, Cambridge]] with a [[Bachelor of Music]] and may have received a [[Doctor of Music]] from [[Oxford]] in May of 1622. The most important position achieved by Gibbons was his appointment in 1623 as the [[List of Westminster Abbey organists|organist]] at [[Westminster Abbey]] which he held for 2 years until his death on the June 5th, 1625.\n\nGibbons was the leading composer in early 17th century England and a pivotal [[Transition from Renaissance to Baroque in instrumental music|transitional figure]] from the end of the [[Renaissance]] to the beginning of the [[Baroque music|Baroque era]]. He was praised in his time by a visit in 1624 from the French ambassador, [[Charles de L'Aubespine]], who stated upon entering Westminster Abbey that \u201cAt the entrance, the organ was touched by the best finger of that age, Mr. Orlando Gibbons.\"{{sfn|Huray|2001}} Musicologist and composer, [[Frederick Ouseley]], dubbed him to be the \"English Palestrina\"<ref>Grove 1900, pp. 71</ref>{{#tag:ref|This is in reference to the revered polyphonic Italian composer, [[Giovanni Palestrina]].|group=n}} and the Canadian pianist [[Glenn Gould]] praised him highly and compared his music, especially for the keyboard, to the likes of [[Beethoven]] and [[Anton Webern|Webern]].<ref>[https://www.orlandogibbons.com/gould-on-gibbons/ \"Gould and Gibbons\" Gould and Gibbons.] N.p, 2019. Web. 19 August 2019.</ref> Gibbons paved the way for a future generation of [[Chronological list of English classical composers|English composers]] by perfecting the Byrd's foundations of the [[English Madrigal School|English madrigal]] as well as both full and verse anthems, and especially by teaching music to his oldest son, [[Christopher Gibbons|Christopher]], who in turn taught [[John Blow]], [[Pelham Humfrey]] and most notably [[Henry Purcell]] the English pioneer of the [[Baroque music|Baroque era]].{{sfn|Turbet|2016}} The modern music critic [[John Rockwell]] claimed that the oeuvre of Gibbons: \"all attested not merely to a significant figure in music's past but to a composer who can still speak directly to the present.\"{{sfn|Rockwell|1984}}\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Birthplace and background===\nUp until the mid 20th century Orlando Gibbons was assumed to have been born in [[Cambridge]].{{sfn|Hawkins|1853|p=573}}{{sfn|Thewlis|1940|p=31}} This was accepted as fact by his contemporaries, stated in multiple early biographies and even recorded on a monument in [[Canterbury Cathedral]], that was erected in his memory soon after his death.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=32}} It is even possible that Gibbons himself thought that he was born in Cambridge, since he spent most of his life in Cambridge and only the first 4\u20135 years of his life in [[Oxford]].{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=32}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=7}} Matters are made more confusing as his father had lived in Cambridge for at least 10 years, 1\u20133 years before the birth of Orlando.{{sfn|Harley|1999|pp=5\u20139}} Therefore even though the 17th century biographer, [[Anthony Wood (antiquary)|Anthony Wood]], discovered a record of an 'Orlando Gibbons' being baptised in [[Carfax, Oxford|St. Martin's Church]], [[Oxford]], it was assumed to be either a mistake, or a reference to a someone else of the same name.{{sfn|Wood|1815|p=406}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=32}} However, modern historians have proved the claim that he was born in Cambridge to be incorrect. Not only was the baptismal record proved to be authentic, but it was discovered that Orlando's parents both resided in Oxford at the time of his birth, confirming that Orlando's birthplace was in [[Carfax, Oxford|St. Martin's Church]], [[Oxford]].{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=33}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=9}}{{sfn|Thewlis|1940|p=33}}\n\n===Early life===\n[[File:The first St Martin\u2019s Church 1822.jpg|thumb|upright|300px|[[James Sargant Storer|James Sargant Storer's]] drawing of, Orlando Gibbon's baptism place, [[Carfax, Oxford|St. Martin's Church]], [[Oxford]], before its renovations in 1820.]]\nGibbons was born to William and Mary Gibbons as probably the 7th{{#tag:ref|Although the birthdates of two of his sisters, Thomasine and Elizabeth, are uncertain leading to the possibility of Gibbons being the 8th or youngest surviving sibling.|group=n}} of 9 surviving children{{#tag:ref|One of the children, Richard, died as an infant.|group=n}} in [[Oxford]], [[Oxfordshire]], where his father was a [[Oxford City Council|city councillor]] and head of the [[wait (musician)|town waits]].{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=17}} There is no surviving record of the date of his birth; however he is recorded to have been baptised at [[Carfax, Oxford|St. Martin's Church]], [[Oxford]]{{#tag:ref|The Church itself was demolished in 1900 and only one of the towers, [[Carfax, Oxford|The Carfax Tower]], survives.|group=n}} on Christmas day, 25 December 1583.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=33}} That being said, following with the norms of the time suggests that Gibbons was likely born no more than a week before his baptism.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}} Gibbons' father had previously lived in Cambridge where he was also the head of the town waits and around 1588, when Orlando was 4\u20135 years old, the Gibbons family moved back to Cambridge and William resumed his previous post there.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=11}}{{sfn|Turbet|2016}}\n\nOrlando was born into a musical family where not only was his father a musician but his oldest brother, [[Edward Gibbons|Edward]], was a composer and master of the choristers at [[Choir of King's College, Cambridge]].{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=28}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=18}} His second brother, [[Ellis Gibbons|Ellis]], was a promising composer but died prematurely, while his third brother, Ferdinando, may have eventually taken their father's place as a wait.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=29}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=16}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=31}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=17}} Not much else is known about Orlando Gibbon's youth, but being born into a musical family meant that he was likely instructed on various instruments by his father or older brothers.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}} At the age of 12, he became a member of Edward's Choir of King's College, Cambridge on 14 February 1596{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=34\u201335}}He was a regular member of the choir until sometime in the [[Michaelmas term]] of 1598 and the [[Easter term]] (summer term) of same year he enrolled [[King's College, Cambridge]] as a [[sizar]], meaning he payed reduced fees but had to do various menial tasks.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=35}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}}<ref name=\"Merriam Webster\">{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/sizar |title=Definition of sizar |publisher=[[Merriam-Webster|Merriam-Webster, Incorporated]] |access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref> However, from 1998\u20131999 Gibbons' name appeared sporadically in the chorus member logs, suggesting that, if not a clerical error, he sang continued to sing irregularly, perhaps for special occasions.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=33}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}} Gibbons' composition teacher is unknown, although it would make sense if it was an older or his father, due to them all being experienced musicians.{{sfn|Cummings}} Edward is often proposed as the most likely candidate by historians, as he was the oldest brother, had achieved a [[Bachelor of Music]] at King's College, Cambridge, and was already experienced as the master of the choruses at.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}} Another possible composition teacher is [[William Byrd]], who was at least 40 years his senior and the most respected English composer at the time.{{sfn|Milsom|2011}} Gibbons and Byrd along with the composer [[John Bull (composer)|John Bull]] later collectively published music and since Bull was a student of Byrd's, Gibbons may very well have been as well.{{sfn|Turbet|2016}} No matter how his musical education came about, Gibbons was known to be composing music by the end of his time at the choir in 1599, at age 15\u201316.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}}{{sfn|Cummings}}\n\n===Early career and marriage===\n[[File:James I of England Schloss Ambras.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Employer of Orlando Gibbons, [[James I of England]]]]\nGibbons' abilities had reached the point to allow him become a Musician of the [[Chapel Royal]] on 19 May 1603.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}} His name appears at this time in a Cheque book from the Chapel Royal for services to [[King James I of England|King James I]], as he was likely Gentleman Extraordinary (unpaid substitute) awaiting the vacancy of a paid position.{{sfn|Huray|2001}} 1603 must have also been an emotionally taxing year, as even though he received his first position as a professional musician, both his mother and brother, Ellis, passed away.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=24}} Eventually Gibbons' awaited vacancy occurred with the death of Arthur Cook, so on 21 March 1605 he secured the prestigious position of [[Gentleman of the Chapel Royal]], as the junior chapel organist.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=29}}{{sfn|Wood|1815|p=406}} Edward Gibbon's friendship with the former organist, Arthur Cook, and the senior chapel organist, [[John Bull (composer)|John Bull]], may have helped his younger brother secure this position.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=30}}{{sfn|Harper|2008}} Either way, becoming a Gentleman of the Chapel Royal at the age of only 21 would have been an impressive feat at the time and he kept this position until the end of his life.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=35}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=31}}\n\nThe next year, 1606, was a busy year as he married Elizabeth Patten on 17 February 1606.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=35}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=32}} Elizabeth was the daughter of John Patten, a [[Yeoman]] of the [[Vestry]] in the Chapel Royal, suggesting that he was well acquainted with Gibbons, something that likely helped arrange the marriage.{{sfn|Harley|1999|pp=32\u201333}} In fact, when John Patten died in 1623, he made Gibbons his sole heir, [[residuary estate|residuary legatee]] and left 200 pounds for his children.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=36}} The same year, shortly after his marriage, Orlando graduated from Cambridge with a Bachelor in Music.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=36}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=33}} Gibbons and his wife lived in Woolstaple (now [[Bridge Street]]) which was in the [[parish]] of [[St Margaret's, Westminster]], the church where Gibbons' seven children{{#tag:ref|Gibbons and Patten's 7 children were, James, Alice, Christopher, Ann, Mary, Elizabeth and Orlando.{{sfn|Westminster Abbey}}|group=n}} would be baptised, including the well known composer, [[Christopher Gibbons]].{{sfn|Harley|1999|pp=35\u201336}}{{sfn|Turbet|2016}}{{sfn|Huray|2001}}\n\n===Publishing and patronage===\nBy the 1610s Gibbons had become a composer of high repute and perhaps the best organist in England.{{sfn|Cummings}}{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=49}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=37}} This is the same time where Gibbons became a close friend of [[Christopher Hatton (died 1619)|Sir Christopher Hatton]], who became an important [[patron]] of his.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=38}} Hatton was the second cousin and heir of the more famous [[Christopher Hatton]], [[favourite]] of [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth I of England]].{{sfn|Harper|2008}} In fact, Hatton and his wife, Alice Fanshawe, were probably the namesakes of 2 of Gibbons' children, Ann Gibbons and the future composer [[Christopher Gibbons]].{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=37}}{{sfn|Harper|2008}}   The next years saw the publishing of various works by Gibbons, the first of which, his ''First Set of Madrigals and Motets'' was published in 1612 under the Patronage of Hatton.{{sfn|Huray|2001}} One of the Madrigals in the set was renowned and probably the most famous English Madrigal, ''[[The Silver Swan (song)|The Silver Swan]]''.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=55}} Gibbons also dedicated the entire set of works to Hatton and claimed that most of it was composed in his house, specifically stating to him that the songs: \n\n{{quote|Were most of them composed in your owne house, and doe therefore properly belong unto you, as Lord of the Soile; the language they speake you provided them, I onely furnished them with Tongues to utter the same name.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=37}}{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=36}}}}<!--Please note that the preceding quote may have grammatical errors in the context of modern english, but was recorded and written here in with exact old english spellings.-->\n\nThis quote has been interpreted in suggesting that Hatton wrote some or all of the poems that Gibbons set to music in his ''First Set of Madrigals and Motets,'' however, there is no evidence other than speculative to support this.{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=35}} Additionally, it is unlikely that Gibbons was a resident of Hatton's household, however their friendship suggests that Hatton may have set a room aside for him to compose.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=39}}\n\n{{multiple image|total_width=350\n|image1=William Byrd.jpg\n|image2=John Bull 1589.jpg\n|footer=Along with Gibbons, [[William Byrd]] and [[John Bull (composer)|John Bull]] were the most important composers in England at the time. They collectively worked in the service of [[James I|James VI and I]] and published [[Parthenia (music)|Parthenia]].}}\nSometime in 1612\u20131613, Gibbons had 6 works published in the first printed collection of keyboard music, [[Parthenia (music)|Parthenia]], which included works by the older and important composers, [[William Byrd]] and [[John Bull]].{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=35}} This publication was to celebrate the marriage of the [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Princess Elizabeth]] to [[Frederick V of the Palatinate|Duke Frederick V, the Elector of Palestine]].{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=43}} Compositions written sometime in the next couple of years, including various anthems dedicated to senior clergy, the pavan ''Lord Salisbury'' for Lord Salisbury and the wedding anthem ''Blessed are all they'' in 1613 for the Earl of Somerset suggest that he was well associated throughout the court.{{sfn|Huray|2001}} In 1614 [[William Leighton]] published ''The Teares and Lamentatacions of a Sorrowfull Soule'' with 2 contributions by Gibbons, ''O Lord how do my woes increase'' and ''O Lord, I lift my heart to Thee''.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=51}} Although he possibly started as early as 1605, Gibbons was the joint organist with [[Edmund Hooper (organist)|Edmund Hooper]] by at least 1615.{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Westminster Abbey}} The same year he received two grants from King James I, worth 150 pounds total.{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|pp=37\u201338}} These grants were: \n\n{{quote|For and in consideration of the good and faithful service heretofore done unto ourself by Orlando Gibbons our organist, and divers other good causes and considerations us thereunto moving.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|pp=37\u201338}}}}\n\nGibbons continued writing for James I, composing the anthem ''Great King of Gods'' and the court song ''Do not repine, fair sun'' in celebration of the King's 1617 visit to Scotland.{{sfn|Huray|2001}}\n\n===Late career===\nBy the late 1610s Gibbons was undoubtedly the most important musician and composer at court as William Byrd had retired in [[Essex]] and John Bull had fled to the [[Low Countries]] to avoid a charge of adultery.{{sfn|Turbet|2016}}{{sfn|Milsom|2011}}{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=34}}{{sfn|Neighbour|2001}} In 1617 Gibbons gained the position as keyboard player in an ensemble, organized by [[John Cooper (composer)|John Cooper]], for the privy chamber of Prince Charles (later [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]]).{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=58}} He was the only keyboardist in a group of 17 musicians of whom the Prince himself was thought to have occasionally joined the musicians on either the [[Viol|Bass-Viol]] or [[Viol|Viol da Gamba]].{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=59}} It is likely that Gibbons was able to write for this ensemble and had pieces premiered by it.{{sfn|Huray|2001}} In addition to this, Gibbons probably gained a 3rd position in September 1619, attending the royal privy chamber of James I.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=62\u201363}} His next major work, ''Fantasies of Three Parts'' was published around 1620 and dedicated it to Edmund Wry. This seemingly random dedication has provoked much speculation. It may be because Wry could secure Gibbons a better post, or it may be an action of gratitude for having already secured him the post for the royal privy chamber of the King.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=63}}\n\nWhile once assumed to be fact, there is now much doubt as to if Gibbons received a Doctor of Music on 17 May 1622. Wood stated in 1815 that \n\n{{quote|\"On the 17th of May, Orlando Gibbons, one of the organists of his majesty's chapel, did supplicate the venerable congregation that he might accumulate the degrees in music; but whether he was admitted to the one, or license to proceed in the other, it appears not.\"{{sfn|Wood|1815|p=406}}}}\n\nThis uncertainty has continued until present day and is made even more confusing by the use of Gibbon's 8 part full anthem, ''O clap your hands'', as the commencement song for [[William Heather|William Heather's]]{{#tag:ref|Often spelled as William Heyther.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=39}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=64}}|group=n}} honorary doctor of music on 17 May 1622.{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=42}}{{sfn|Mateer|2008}} Heather had financially supported [[William Camden|William Camden's]] creation and maintenance of the [[Camden Professor of Ancient History|Camden Professor of Ancient History chair]] and in return the university awarded Heather an honorary bachelor in music and Doctor of Music, even though he was not known to be a musician.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=39}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=65}} Author [[John Hawkins (author)|Sir John Hawkins]] and musicologists [[Edmund Fellowes]] and David Mateer confidently state that Gibbons achieved a Doctor of Music the same day as Heather and cite ''O clap your hands'' to actually be Gibbon's qualifying exercise for his degree.{{sfn|Hawkins|1853|p=573}}{{sfn|Mateer|2008}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=39}} Where as musicologists Peter Le Huray, John Harper and John Harley propose some concerns as to if Gibbons really achieved a Doctor in Music.{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=64\u201366}} Specifically, Harley cites a record in the Cheque book of the Chapel Royal that refers to William Heather as \"doctor\" but Gibbons as \"senior organist.\"{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=66}} Harley also addresses a letter from Camden to William Piers from 18 May 1622, that says Gibbons is a Doctor of Music.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=65}} He suggests that the authenticity of the letter is uncertain, since the original letter doesn't survive, and that Camden could have written something such as \"G\u2013\u2013\u2013\u2013s\" which an editor assumed to mean Gibbons.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=66}} However, the most convincing piece of evidence seems to be the absence of mentioning the supposed Doctor of Music on Gibbons' Cambridge monument that was erected in his memory when he died.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=65}} While the existing evidence seems to support that he never achieved a Doctor in Music, there is no indisputable evidence to confirm this claim.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=66}} \n\n===Final years and death===\n\nSometime in 1623, [[George Wither]] published ''Hymnes and Songs of the Church'' where Gibbons provided the tunes for most of the songs.{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=43}}{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=67}} The same year he succeeded [[John Parsons (organist)|John Parsons]] as the [[List of Westminster Abbey organists|organist]] at [[Westminster Abbey]], with [[Thomas Day]] as junior organist.{{sfn|Harley|1999|p=68}} This was probably the most important position Gibbons had taken in his career thus far and on 7 May 1625 he officiated at the funeral of King James I.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=40}} \n\nDuring late May 1625, the English court was preparing to receive [[Henrietta Maria of France|Queen Henrietta Maria]], whom the now [[Charles I of England|King Charles I of England]] had recently [[Proxy marriage|married through proxy]] in France on 1 May 1625.{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=41}} Gibbons and other Chapel Royal members had begun traveling to [[Canterbury]] on 31 May when Gibbons suddenly came down with an illness, probably a [[cerebral aneurysm]].{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=44}} He died at age 41 in [[Canterbury]] and was buried in [[Canterbury Cathedral]].{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=44}}{{sfn|Bridge|1920|p=47}} His death was a shock to his peers and brought about a post-mortem, though the cause of death aroused less comment than the haste of his burial and his body not being returned to London.{{sfn|Huray|2001}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=45}} His wife, Elizabeth, died a little over a year later, in her mid-30s, leaving Orlando's eldest brother, Edward, to care for the orphaned children.{{sfn|Wood|1815|p=406}}{{sfn|Fellowes|1951|p=50}}\n\n==Music==\nOne of the most versatile English composers of his time, Gibbons wrote a large number of keyboard works, around thirty [[Fantasia (music)|fantasias]] for [[viol]]s, a number of [[madrigal]]s (the best-known being \"[[The Silver Swan (song)|The Silver Swan]]\"), and many popular [[verse anthem]]s, all to English texts (the best known being \"Great Lord of Lords\"). Perhaps his best-known verse anthem is ''[[This Is the Record of John]]'', which sets an [[Advent]] text for solo [[countertenor]] or [[tenor]], alternating with full chorus. The soloist is required to demonstrate considerable technical facility, and the work expresses the text's rhetorical force without being demonstrative or bombastic. He also produced two major settings of [[Evening Prayer (Anglican)|Evensong]], the Short Service and the Second Service, an extended composition combining verse and full sections. Gibbons's full anthems include the expressive ''O Lord, in thy wrath'', and the [[Feast of the Ascension|Ascension Day]] anthem ''O clap your hands together'' (after Psalm 47) for eight voices.\n\nHe contributed six pieces to the first printed collection of keyboard music in England, ''[[Parthenia (music)|Parthenia]]'' (to which he was by far the youngest of the three contributors), published in about 1611. Gibbons's surviving keyboard output comprises some 45 pieces. The polyphonic fantasia and dance forms are the best represented genres. Gibbons's writing exhibits a command of three- and four-part counterpoint. Most of the fantasias are complex, multi-sectional pieces, treating multiple subjects imitatively. Gibbons's approach to melody, in both his fantasias and his dances, features extensive development of simple musical ideas, as for example in ''Pavane in D minor'' and ''Lord Salisbury's Pavan and Galliard''.<ref>[[Willi Apel|Apel, Willi]]. 1972. ''The History of Keyboard Music to 1700'', pp.&nbsp;320\u2013323. Translated by Hans Tischler. Indiana University Press. {{ISBN|0-253-21141-7}}. Originally published as ''Geschichte der Orgel- und Klaviermusik bis 1700'' by B\u00e4renreiter-Verlag, Kassel.</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n{{listen|filename=Orlando_Gibbons_Out_of_the_deep_(The_Tudor_Consort).ogg|title= ''Out of the Deep'' by Orlando Gibbons|description=Recorded live in Borja, Spain, by [[the Tudor Consort]] in October 2005|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n{{listen|filename=Orlando Gibbons (bap.1583-1625) - Fantasia \u00e03, No.3 for Treble & Bass Viols with Great Bass.ogg|title=Fantasia \u00e03, No.3 for Treble & Bass Viols with Great Bass by Orlando Gibbons|description=Recorded by Phillip W. Serna in July 2019|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n{{listen|filename=Orlando Gibbons (bap.1583-1625) - Fantasia \u00e02, VdGS No.4 for 2 Treble Viols.ogg|title=Fantasia \u00e02, VdGS No.4 for 2 Treble Viols by Orlando Gibbons|description=Recorded by Phillip W. Serna in August 2019|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n{{listen|filename=Orlando Gibbons (bap.1583-1625) - Galliard \u00e03, for Treble & Bass Viols with Great Bass.oga|title=Galliard \u00e03 for Treble & Bass Viols with Great Bass by Orlando Gibbons|description=Recorded by Phillip W. Serna in July 2019|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n{{listen|filename=Orlando Gibbons (bap.1583-1625) - Fantasia \u00e02, VdGS No.3 for 2 Treble Viols.ogg|title=Fantasia \u00e02, VdGS No.3 for 2 Treble Viols by Orlando Gibbons|description=Recorded by Phillip W. Serna in August 2019|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n{{listen|filename=Orlando Gibbons (bap.1583-1625) - Fantasia \u00e04, No.1 for Treble, Tenor & Bass Viols with Great Bass.oga|title=Fantasia \u00e04, No.1 for Treble, Tenor & Bass Viols with Great Bass by Orlando Gibbons|description=Recorded by Phillip W. Serna in July 2019|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n===First Set of Madrigals and Motets (1612)===\n'First Set of Madrigals and Mottets, apt for Viols and Voyces'. Twenty pieces, all by Gibbons.\n# The silver swanne\n# O that the learned Poets of our time\n# I waigh not fortunes frowne nor smile\n# I tremble not at noyse of warre\n# I see Ambition never pleasde\n# I faine not friendship where I hate\n# How art thou thrald, O poor despised creature?\n# Farewell all joyes\n# Daintie fine bird which art incaged there\n# Fair ladies that to Love captived are\n# Mongst thousands good\n# Now each flowery bancke of May\n# Lais now old, that erst attempting Lasse\n# Faire is the rose\n# What is our life?\n# Ah, deere Hart, why do you rise?\n# Nay, let me weepe\n# Nere let the Sunne with his deceiving light\n# Yet if that age had frosted ore his head\n# Trust not too much, faire youth unto thy feature\n\n===Parthenia (1613)===\nThe Parthenia or the Maydenhead of the first musicke that ever was printed for the Virginalls contains six keyboard works by Gibbons.\n\n# Galiardo\n# Fantazia of Foure Parts\n# The Lord Salisbury his Pavin\n# Galiardo\n# The Queenes Command\n# Preludium\n\n===Tears or Lamentations (1614)===\nLeighton's 'Teares or Lamentacions of a Sorrowfull Soule', published 1614, contains several works by Gibbons.\n\n===Fantasias (1620)===\nNine three-part works, all by Gibbons.\n\n=== Hymnes and Songs of the Church (1623)===\nGeorge Withers' 'Hymnes and Songs of the Church', published 1623, contains 16 works by Gibbons in the original edition and adds a 17th in a later edition.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the 20th century, the Canadian pianist [[Glenn Gould]] championed Gibbons's music, and named him as his favourite composer.<ref>Cott, Jonathan, and Gould, Glenn. 2005. ''Conversations with Glenn Gould'', p.&nbsp;65. University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|978-0-226-11623-5}}</ref> Gould wrote of Gibbons's hymns and anthems: \"ever since my teen-age years this music ... has moved me more deeply than any other sound experience I can think of.\"<ref>Gould, Glenn, and Page, Tim, ed. 1984. ''The Glenn Gould Reader''. p.&nbsp;438. New York: Knopf. {{ISBN|0-394-54067-0}}</ref>\nIn one interview, Gould compared Gibbons to [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]] and [[Anton Webern|Webern]]:\n<blockquote>...despite the requisite quota of scales and shakes in such half-hearted virtuoso vehicles as the ''Salisbury Galliard'', one is never quite able to counter the impression of music of supreme beauty that lacks its ideal means of reproduction. Like Beethoven in his last quartets, or Webern at almost any time, Gibbons is an artist of such intractable commitment that, in the keyboard field, at least, his works work better in one's memory, or on paper, than they ever can through the intercession of a sounding-board.<ref>Payzant, Geoffrey. 1986. ''Glenn Gould: Music & Mind'', pp.&nbsp;82\u201383. Formac Publishing Company, Goodread Biographies Series: Volume 45 of Canadian Lives. {{ISBN|978-0-88780-145-7}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nGibbons's death, on 5 June 1625, is regularly marked in [[King's College Chapel, Cambridge]], by the singing of his music at Evensong.<ref>[http://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/choir/about/history.html The Choir of King's College, Cambridge \u00bb History of the Choir] ''www.kings.cam.ac.uk'', accessed 28 February 2020</ref> A number of Gibbons's church anthems were included in the ''[[Oxford Book of Tudor Anthems]]'' (OUP, 1978).<ref name=\"oup\">{{cite book|last1=Morris|first1=Christopher|title=The Oxford book of Tudor anthems: 34 Anthems for Mixed Voices|date=1978|publisher=Music Department, Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0193533257}}</ref>\n\n==Post-mortem==\nA suspicion immediately arose that Gibbons had died of the [[Plague (disease)|plague]], which was rife in England that year. Two physicians who had been present at his death were ordered to make a report, and performed a [[autopsy|post-mortem examination]], the account of which survives in [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]:\n<blockquote>We whose names are here underwritten: having been called to give our counsels to Mr. Orlando Gibbons; in the time of his late and sudden sickness, which we found in the beginning lethargical, or a profound sleep; out of which, we could never recover him, neither by inward nor outward medicines, & then instantly he fell in most strong, & sharp convulsions; which did wring his mouth up to his ears, & his eyes were distorted, as though they would have been thrust out of his head & then suddenly he lost both speech, sight and hearing, & so grew apoplectical & lost the whole motion of every part of his body, & so died. Then here upon (his death being so sudden) rumours were cast out that he did die of the plague, whereupon we . . . caused his body to be searched by certain women that were sworn to deliver the truth, who did affirm that they never saw a fairer corpse. Yet notwithstanding we to give full satisfaction to all did cause the skull to be opened in our presence & we carefully viewed the body, which we found also to be very clean without any show or spot of any contagious matter. In the brain we found the whole & sole cause of his sickness namely a great admirable blackness & syderation in the outside of the brain. Within the brain (being opened) there did issue out abundance of water intermixed with blood & this we affirm to be the only cause of his sudden death.<ref>[[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]], ''State Papers Domestic'', [[Charles I of England|Charles I]], 1625, III, 60, quoted in ''Thomas Tomkins: The Last Elizabethan'' by Anthony Boden (Ed) (Ashgate Publishing, Aldershot 2005, {{ISBN|0-754-6511-85}}, p.124).</ref></blockquote>\n\nThis account is taken to mean that Gibbons died of a [[cerebral aneurysm]].<ref>{{cite book|title=What Killed the Great and Not So Great Composers?|author=Joseph W. Lewis|ISBN=978-1449075842}}</ref>\n\n==Selected Recordings==\n*''Complete Keyboard Works'', (2008), Daniel-Ben Pienaar, Deux Elles, ASIN: B000W043UQ [http://danielbenpienaar.com/essays/Revisting%20The%20Keyboard%20Music%20Of%20Orlando%20Gibbons.htm]\n*''Gibbons: Choral and Organ Music'', (1996), Laurence Cummings, Oxford Camerata, ASIN: B000QQT8VK [https://www.amazon.com/Choral-Organ-Music-Gibbons/dp/B00000144V/ref=tmm_acd_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=1583203895&sr=1-1]\n*''Gibbons: Consort And Keyboard Music / Songs And Anthems'', (1994), Timothy Roberts, Tessa Bonner, Rose Consort of Viols, ASIN: B000QQUCR4 [https://www.amazon.com/Gibbons-Consort-Keyboard-Music-Anthems/dp/B0000013UO/ref=tmm_acd_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=1583203439&sr=1-2]\n*''Orlando Gibbons: Peace On Earth'', (2007), Robert Sharpe, Christopher Gray, Truro Cathedral Choir, ASIN: B000Y2RWZK [https://www.amazon.com/Orlando-Gibbons-Truro-Cathedral-Choir/dp/B000Y2RWZK/ref=sr_1_1?keywords=Orlando+Gibbons&qid=1583203439&s=dmusic&sr=1-1]\n\n== See also ==\nThere are only two extensive books written about Orlando Gibbons and his family.{{sfn|Turbet|2016}}\n#[https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9780208008480 Orlando Gibbons and his family: the last of the Tudor school of musicians, by Edmund H. Fellowes]\n#[https://isbnsearch.org/isbn/9781840142099 Orlando Gibbons and the Gibbons family of musicians, by John Harley]   \n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=n|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|18em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin|colwidth=45em}}\n'''Books'''\n* {{cite book\n |last=Bridge\n |first=Sir Frederick\n |author-link=Frederick Bridge\n |year=2009\n |orig-year=1920\n |title=Twelve Good Musicians: From John Bull to Henry Purcell\n |publisher=[[Cornell University Library]]\n |language=English\n |location=London, England\n |isbn=978-1112520761\n |url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/39935/39935-h/39935-h.htm#chap05\n |ref={{sfnRef|Bridge|1920}}\n}}\n\n* {{cite book\n |last=Fellowes\n |first=Edmund H.\n |author-link=Edmund Fellowes\n |year=1951\n |title=Orlando Gibbons and His Family: The Last of the Tudor School of Musicians\n |edition=2nd\n |publisher=Archon Books\n |language=English\n |location=United States\n |isbn=978-0-208-00848-0\n |url-access=registration \n |url=https://archive.org/details/orlandogibbonshi0000fell\n